"<page><title>Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun</title><text>{{Infobox VG | title = Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun | image = [[File:LoK-DeadSun-Screenshot.jpg|256px]] | caption = The protagonist, Gein/Asher | developer = [[Climax Studios]]{{Collapsible list|title=Additional work by:|[[Psyonix]] <small>(multiplayer)</small>}} | publisher = [[Square Enix Europe]] | director = [[Sam Barlow (video game director)|Sam Barlow]]<ref name="LinkedIn-SamBarlow">{{cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/pub/sam-barlow/1/23b/650 |title=Sam Barlow |last=Barlow |first=Sam |authorlink=Sam Barlow |publisher=[[LinkedIn]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> | series = ''[[Legacy of Kain]]'' | engine = [[Unreal engine#Unreal Engine 3|Unreal Engine 3]]<ref name="Helenasia-BlackCloth">{{cite web |url=http://www.helenasia.com/blackcloth.htm |title=Project- Black Cloth |last=Simm |first=Helen |publisher=Helenasia |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="Sebashq-MyPortfolio">{{cite web |url=http://sebashq.com/#my-portfolio |title=My Portfolio |last=Mandalà |first=Sebastiano |publisher=Sebashq |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]],<ref name="LinkedIn-RobertMcLachlan">{{cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/pub/robert-mclachlan/0/a42/a6 |title=Robert McLachlan |last=McLachlan |first=Robert |publisher=[[LinkedIn]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><br />[[PlayStation 3]],<ref name="LinkedIn-SamBarlow"/><br />[[PlayStation 4]],<ref name="Edge-2014-02-07"/><br />[[Xbox 360]]<ref name="LinkedIn-SamBarlow"/> | released = Cancelled | genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] }}  '''''Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun''''' was an [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game developed by [[Climax Studios]] for [[Square Enix Europe]], with an accompanying multiplayer component developed separately by [[Psyonix]]. Conceived as the sixth entry in the ''[[Legacy of Kain]]'' series, ''Dead Sun'' entered production for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox 360]], but was cancelled in 2012 following three years of work, and initially remained undisclosed to the public. Square Enix Europe and Psyonix salvaged the planned multiplayer mode, which they reconceptualized as ''[[Nosgoth]]'', a standalone [[free-to-play]] title.  Shortly after ''Nosgoth''{{'}}s announcement in 2013, a poster at the [[internet forum]] [[NeoGAF]] unearthed ''Dead Sun'' in an extensive report, publicizing media and accounts from sources in Climax Studios. Square Enix Europe subsequently acknowledged the scrapped project with the conclusion that ''Dead Sun'' "just wasn't the right game, at the right time."<ref name="Eurogamer-2013-06-19">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-06-19-square-enix-acknowledges-cancelled-legacy-of-kain-game-dead-sun |title=Square Enix acknowledges cancelled Legacy of Kain game Dead Sun |last=Purchese |first=Robert |date=19 June 2013 |publisher=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Further articles, revealing gameplay footage and concept art, ensued later in the year. Video game publications responded negatively to news of the cancellation, and most commentators expressed their sustained interest in a single-player revival of the franchise.  ==Gameplay== Leaks described ''Dead Sun'' as a story-based [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] inspired by 1999's ''[[Legacy of Kain: Soul Reaver]]'' (the second installment in the series) and [[Nintendo]]'s ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''. The game featured an [[open world]], and combined cinematic, violent combat with [[dungeon crawl]]s, puzzles, and [[boss (video gaming)|boss]] encounters. Links to past ''[[Legacy of Kain]]'' entries figured into the design, such as the shifting mechanic of the ''Soul Reaver'' titles, which enabled players to alternate between two planes of existence.<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-18">{{cite web |url=http://www.neogaf.com/forum/showthread.php?t=594576 |title=The 10 Cancelled Legacy of Kains (Mama Robotnik Research Thread) (post #1) |author=Mama Robotnik |date=18 June 2013 |publisher=[[NeoGAF]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  Videos of the project's [[vertical slice]] presentation demonstrated the codex – an in-game encyclopedia supplying background history on the world – and a [[power-up]] system, in which collectible souls could be exchanged for upgrades to assist in battle or exploration.<ref name="Polygon-2013-08-14">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/8/14/4620268/legacy-of-kain-dead-sun-and-nosgoth-details-emerge |title=More Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun and Nosgoth details emerge |last=Pitcher |first=Jenna |date=14 August 2013 |publisher=[[Polygon]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  ==Plot== ''Dead Sun'' took place in the far future of the ''Legacy of Kain'' world, long after the events of ''Soul Reaver'' and 2003's ''[[Legacy of Kain: Defiance]]''. Players would control new protagonists Gein, a [[vampire]], and Asher, a human, whose souls became intertwined as they travelled the land of Nosgoth.<ref name="VG247-2013-06-18">{{cite web |url=http://www.vg247.com/2013/06/18/legacy-of-kain-10-cancelled-titles-exposed-by-neogaf-investigation-report/ |title=Legacy of Kain: 10 cancelled titles exposed by NeoGAF investigation – report |last=Cook |first=Dave |authorlink=Dave Cook |date=18 June 2013 |publisher=[[VG247]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="WhatCulture-2014-09-08">{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/11-hugely-anticipated-video-games-wont-believe-got-cancelled.php/4 |title=11 Hugely-Anticipated Video Games You Won’t Believe Got Cancelled - Page 4 of 12 |last=Tailford |first=Scott |date=8 September 2014 |publisher=WhatCulture |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  According to leaked material, Gein/Asher's character arc would escalate from a quest for revenge to a journey which would decide the fate of the world. The plot concerned the mystery surrounding a vampire child, and revolved around the character of [[Elder God (Legacy of Kain)|The Elder God]]. Thematically, it focused on religion.<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-18"/>  Square Enix Europe community manager George Kelion said that the game would have [[Reboot (fiction)|rebooted]] or [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] the series' established mythology, and only utilized returning characters "in the broadest possible terms." Kelion likened its prospective impact on the fiction to that of the [[Star Trek (film franchise)#Reboot|''Star Trek'' reboot series]].<ref name="NeoGAF-2014-02-07-#1">{{cite web |url=http://www.neogaf.com/forum/showpost.php?p=99977444&postcount=188 |title=Nosgoth Gameplay Premiere (post #188) |author=Monkeythumbz |date=7 February 2014 |publisher=[[NeoGAF]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="NeoGAF-2014-02-07-#2">{{cite web |url=http://www.neogaf.com/forum/showpost.php?p=99978215&postcount=196 |title=Nosgoth Gameplay Premiere (post #196) |author=Monkeythumbz |date=7 February 2014 |publisher=[[NeoGAF]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="NeoGAF-2014-02-07-#3">{{cite web |url=http://www.neogaf.com/forum/showpost.php?p=99983459&postcount=239 |title=Nosgoth Gameplay Premiere (post #239) |author=Monkeythumbz |date=7 February 2014 |publisher=[[NeoGAF]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  The [[Hylden]] race did not appear in the story.<ref name="SquareEnixForums-2014-06-19">{{cite web |url=http://forums.eu.square-enix.com/showthread.php?t=139957&page=3&p=1974292#post1974292 |title=The 10 Cancelled Legacy of Kains (post #52) |author=Monkeythumbz |date=19 June 2013 |publisher=Square Enix Forums |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Concept art indicated that the Silenced Cathedral from ''Soul Reaver'' would reappear.<ref name="RelyOnHorror-2013-08-15">{{cite web |url=http://www.relyonhorror.com/latest-news/legacy-of-kain-dead-sun-looked-awesome-nosgoth-gets-detailed/ |title=Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun looked awesome, Nosgoth gets detailed |last=Melendez |first=C. J. |date=15 August 2013 |publisher=Rely on Horror |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  ==Development== ===Production=== Publisher [[Eidos Interactive]] assigned series creators Crystal Dynamics to the ''[[Tomb Raider (franchise)|Tomb Raider]]'' franchise before ''Defiance'' shipped,<ref name="PRNewswire-2005-04-05">{{cite web |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/eidos-unveils-first-details-of-lara-croft-tomb-raider-legend-54191412.html |title=Eidos Unveils First Details of Lara Croft Tomb Raider: Legend |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=5 April 2005 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="GameInformer-2012-11">{{cite journal |last=Justice |first=Brandon |date=November 2012 |title=From uncertainty to opportunity, this storyteller's journey is anything but ordinary |journal=''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' |publisher=EGM Media, LLC |volume=257}}</ref> and writer and director [[Amy Hennig]], unable to proceed with ''Legacy of Kain'' or lead ''[[Tomb Raider: Legend]]'', departed to join [[Naughty Dog]].<ref name="GameInformer-2012-11"/> In 2004, a sequel – ''Legacy of Kain: The Dark Prophecy'' – was delegated to [[Ritual Entertainment]], but Eidos cancelled the title after a few months of work.<ref name="Destructoid-2010-07-26">{{cite web |url=http://ps2.gamespy.com/playstation-2/jak-iii/507370p1.html |title=Canceled game: Legacy of Kain: The Dark Prophecy |last=Sterling |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim Sterling |date=26 July 2010 |publisher=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="DCabDesign-2012-08-13">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcabdesign.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=21#p21 |title=A few questions (post #2) |last=Cabuco |first=Daniel |date=13 August 2012 |publisher=DCabDesign |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Consequently, the ''Legacy of Kain'' brand spent several years under review.<ref name="SquareEnixForums-2004-05-06">{{cite web |url=http://forums.eu.square-enix.com/showthread.php?t=49410&p=450554#post450554 |title=OPM #81 Rumors, answers please!!! (post #9) |author=Chris@Crystal |date=6 May 2004 |publisher=Square Enix Forums |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> However, both Eidos and Crystal Dynamics representatives frequently recognized fan demand for another game, and considered outsourcing the task to other teams.<ref name="GameInformer-2008-03">{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 2008 |title=Bill Gardner Interview |journal=''[[Game Informer]]'' |publisher=[[GameStop]] |volume=179 |page=34}}</ref><ref name="XboxWorld-2008-03">{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 2008 |title=Tomb Raider Underworld |journal=''[[Xbox World]]'' |publisher=[[Future plc]] |volume=179 |page=47}}</ref><ref name="Siliconera-2010-06-09">{{cite web |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2010/06/09/crystal-dynamics-on-making-lara-croft-downloadable/ |title=Crystal Dynamics On Making Lara Croft Downloadable |last=Yip |first=Spencer |date=9 June 2010 |publisher=Siliconera |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="Electricpig-2010-12-20">{{cite web |url=http://www.electricpig.co.uk/2010/12/20/gangsters-legacy-of-kain-sequels-on-the-way/ |title=Gangsters, Legacy of Kain sequels on the way? |last=Ebert |first=Stephen |date=20 December 2010 |publisher=Electricpig |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  [[Square Enix]] purchased Eidos in 2009,<ref name="Gamasutra-2009-07-07">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/115289/Square_Enix_Europe_Formed_From_Eidos_Acquisition.php |title=Square Enix Europe Formed From Eidos Acquisition |last=Alexander |first=Leigh |date=7 July 2009 |publisher=[[Gamasutra]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> and the newly merged entity, Square Enix Europe, selected [[Climax Studios]] – who had recently completed development of [[Konami]]'s ''[[Silent Hill: Shattered Memories]]'' – to press on with a ''Legacy of Kain'' project for [[History of video game consoles (seventh generation)|seventh generation consoles]].<ref name="Edge-2014-02-07">{{cite web |url=http://www.edge-online.com/features/the-making-of-silent-hill-shattered-memories/ |title=The Making Of: Silent Hill Shattered Memories |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=7 February 2014 |publisher=''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  Leaks alleged that preproduction on ''Dead Sun'' secretly began circa 2009-2010,<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-18"/> under the [[codename]] "Black Cloth".<ref name="Helenasia-BlackCloth"/> The title's budget was small at first,<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-18"/> but in its final incarnation it had achieved [[AAA (game industry)|AAA]] classification,<ref name="Arohart-2013-07-15">{{cite web |url=http://arohart.com/?p=877 |title=The internet can’t keep any secrets |last=Rohart |first=Arthur |date=15 July 2013 |publisher=Arohart |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> and targeted release as a [[PlayStation 4]] [[launch game]].<ref name="Edge-2014-02-07"/> Crystal Dynamics supervised Climax, while Square Enix Europe required that the finished product comprise a single-player and multiplayer package. They recruited [[Psyonix]] to build the latter, then codenamed ''War for Nosgoth''.<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-18"/><ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-20-#2">{{cite web |url=http://www.neogaf.com/forum/showpost.php?p=65095226&postcount=200 |title=The 10 Cancelled Legacy of Kains (Mama Robotnik Research Thread) (post #200) |author=Monkeythumbz |date=20 June 2013 |publisher=[[NeoGAF]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Both teams made use of the [[Unreal Engine 3]],<ref name="Helenasia-BlackCloth"/><ref name="Sebashq-MyPortfolio"/><ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-18"/> and shared a unified art direction, but the two modes were otherwise entirely distinct. The publisher mandated the decision to introduce a new main character (in lieu of series protagonist [[Kain (Legacy of Kain)|Kain]]), requesting that Climax's story showcase a distant time period.<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-18"/> Director [[Sam Barlow (video game director)|Sam Barlow]] would reflect: "we took a lot of things we’d learned from ''Shattered Memories'' and were doing them on a much bigger scale, although more subtly."<ref name="Edge-2014-02-07"/>  Square Enix Europe cancelled ''Dead Sun'' in 2012,<ref name="Arohart-2013-07-15"/><ref name="Artofcode-DeadSun">{{cite web |url=http://artofcode.nl/portfolio/deadsun/ |title=Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun |last=Fekkes |first=Nerbert |publisher=art of code |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> after motion capture and casting had begun,<ref name="RockPaperShotgun-2015-01-23">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/01/23/text-lies-and-videotape-her-story-interview/ |title=Text, Lies And Videotape: Her Story Interview |last=Smith |first=Adam |date=23 January 2015 |publisher=Rock, Paper, Shotgun |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> but before the project reached full production.<ref name="Helenasia-BlackCloth"/> Psyonix continued to develop the ''War for Nosgoth'' multiplayer, now disconnected from the original game.<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-20-#2"/>  Hints of the game had first emerged in 2011, when Game Revolution's Daniel Bischoff cited a consumer survey to determine the best of four possible names tailored for a ''Legacy of Kain'' product: ''Obsidian Blood'', ''Obsidian Sun'', ''Dead Sun'', or ''Revenant''.<ref name="GameRevolution-2011-05-20">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/survey-says-new-legacy-of-kain-game-coming-5797 |title=Survey Says: New Legacy of Kain Game Coming? |last=Bischoff |first=Daniel |date=20 May 2011 |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> In 2012, Patrick Garratt of [[VG247]] relayed rumors of a ''Soul Reaver'' reboot with a "new art direction" then underway at Crystal Dynamics.<ref name="VG247-2012-03-20">{{cite web |url=http://www.vg247.com/2012/03/20/rumour-crystal-dynamics-working-on-soul-reaver-reboot/ |title=Rumour: Crystal Dynamics on “Soul Reaver” reboot |last=Garratt |first=Patrick |date=20 March 2012 |publisher=[[VG247]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Still, no statement occurred until 2013, when ''Official Xbox Magazine'' Edwin Evans-Thirlwell discovered a ''Legacy of Kain'' storyboard by Passion Pictures,<ref name="OXM-2013-02-11">{{cite web |url=http://www.totalxbox.com/50109/new-legacy-of-kain-project-revealed-possible-artwork-spotted-in-portfolio/ |title=New Legacy of Kain project revealed - possible artwork spotted in portfolio |last=Evans-Thirlwell |first=Edwin |date=11 February 2013 |publisher=''[[Official Xbox Magazine]]'' |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> and others found evidence of ''War for Nosgoth'' in the [[Steam]] Database, [[Advanced Micro Devices]]' patch logs, a newly registered domain, and a [[LinkedIn]] profile.<ref name="Polygon-2013-05-26">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/windows/2013/5/26/4369066/nosgoth-appears-on-steam-database-war-of-nosgoth-mentioned-in-amd |title=Nosgoth appears on Steam database, War for Nosgoth mentioned in AMD driver patch logs |last=Pitcher |first=Jenna |date=26 May 2013 |publisher=[[Polygon]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Square Enix Europe's George Kelion confirmed the existence of a multiplayer title named ''[[Nosgoth]]'', promising more information at a later date.<ref name="CVG-2013-06-07">{{cite web |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/411534/legacy-of-kain-nosgoth-is-in-development-square-enix-confirms/ |title=Legacy of Kain: Nosgoth is in development, Square Enix confirms |last=Hussain |first=Tamoor |date=7 June 2013 |publisher=''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>  ===Reveal=== Shortly after Kelion's statement, ''Legacy of Kain'' fan Mama Robotnik revealed ''Dead Sun'' to the public, posting media from the scrapped game and an extensive account of its development at [[NeoGAF]]. Kelion responded by confirming that ''Dead Sun'' existed and that ''Nosgoth'' was intended to be its multiplayer companion game, but said ''Nosgoth'' is a separate project which has "grown in size and scope since its initial conception", featuring "different mechanics, characters, levels and gameplay". He rejected the idea that it is ''"the multiplayer component of Dead Sun pulled out and fleshed out"''.<ref name="Eurogamer-2013-06-19"/>  {{quote|I’ve been watching this post and I thought you might want a bit more information. I can confirm that ''Dead Sun'' was a project which had been in development - but which was cancelled.  I know it’s disappointing to hear about these things out of context, and whilst some of the details released are accurate - some details are not. You know game projects can be cancelled for a variety of different reasons and I know it’s very hard to tell from images and info alone, but in the end ''LoK: Dead Sun'' just wasn’t the right game, at the right time… but you’ll have to take me at my word on that, I’m afraid.<ref name="NeoGAF-2013-06-20-#1">{{cite web |url=http://www.neogaf.com/forum/showpost.php?p=64743986&postcount=181 |title=The 10 Cancelled Legacy of Kains (Mama Robotnik Research Thread) (post #181) |author=Monkeythumbz |date=June 20, 2013 |publisher=[[NeoGAF]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>}}  Climax CEO Simon Gardner remarked on the news to [[Eurogamer]]: {{quote|As you would expect, we are covered under NDA and really don't have anything to add. Many games never see the light of day for lots of different reasons, especially over the last few years where business models and markets have been evolving rapidly. We continue to have a good relationship with Square Enix.<ref name="Eurogamer-2013-06-19"/>}}  Several Climax employees corroborated the project's existence at their résumés,<ref name="LinkedIn-SamBarlow"/><ref name="LinkedIn-RobertMcLachlan"/> portfolios,<ref name="Helenasia-BlackCloth"/><ref name="Sebashq-MyPortfolio"/><ref name="Artofcode-DeadSun"/> and blogs.<ref name="Arohart-2013-07-15"/><ref name="Tumblr-2013-09-01">{{cite web |url=http://muonbee.tumblr.com/post/60003041881/interesting-to-see-legacy-of-kain-dead-sun-work |title=Interesting to see Legacy of Kain dead sun work... |last=Atack |first=Josh |date=1 September 2013 |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Months later, in a follow-up post, Mama Robotnik highlighted other assets, among them concept and trailer art by Flipbook Studio, and in-game footage displaying the [[user interface]].<ref name="Polygon-2013-08-14"/>  ==Reaction== The exposé surrounding ''Dead Sun'' and ''Nosgoth'' attracted criticism from the video game press. Austin Wood of [[Cheat Code Central]] wrote that the project's cancellation "came as a letdown to many",<ref name="CheatCodeCentral-2013-06-19">{{cite web |url=http://news.cheatcc.com/391218 |title=Square Enix Comments On Legacy Of Kain Cancellation |last=Wood |first=Austin |date=19 June 2013 |publisher=[[Cheat Code Central]] |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> whereas GameRanx's Ryan Parreno regarded the junking as "a genuine waste".<ref name="Gameranx-2013-08-14">{{cite web |url=http://www.gameranx.com/updates/id/16742/article/legacy-of-kain-dead-sun-for-ps4-confirmed-cancelled/ |title=Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun for PS4 confirmed cancelled |last=Parreno |first=Ryan |date=14 August 2013 |publisher=Gameranx |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Writing for Rely on Horror, C. J. Melendez said, "in an alternate universe, [''Dead Sun'' and ''Nosgoth''] would switch places. I know that may seem a bit harsh, but fans have waited a long time for a proper singleplayer entry in the Legacy of Kain series." He clarified that "''Nosgoth'' may very well be a good game, but it’s fair to say that it’s probably not going to scratch that itch that fans have had since ''Defiance''."<ref name="RelyOnHorror-2013-08-15"/> Also on ''Nosgoth'', TechnologyTell's Jenni Lada commented, "I can’t bring myself to show any kind of support for what could end up being a free-to-play, cash grab, knowing that Square Enix canned ''Legacy of Kain: Dead Sun'' and supported this instead."<ref name="TechnologyTell-2013-09-25">{{cite web |url=http://www.technologytell.com/gaming/118309/legacy-of-kain-legacy-tragically-reduced-to-free-to-play-nosgoth/ |title=Legacy of Kain legacy tragically reduced to free-to-play Nosgoth |last=Lada |first=Jenni |date=25 September 2013 |publisher=Technology Tell |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Scott Tailford of WhatCulture later included the title as #9 on his list of "11 Hugely-Anticipated Video Games You Won’t Believe Got Cancelled", writing that "for fans that have stuck by the series for almost two decades it's completely maddening".<ref name="WhatCulture-2014-09-08"/>  ==References== {{Reflist|30em}}  {{Legacy of Kain series}}  [[Category:Cancelled PlayStation 3 games]] [[Category:Cancelled PlayStation 4 games]] [[Category:Cancelled Windows games]] [[Category:Cancelled Xbox One games]] [[Category:Legacy of Kain]]</text></page>",
"<page><title>Croatian Democratic Union</title><text>{{Refimprove|date=September 2009}} {{Infobox political party |colorcode       = {{Croatian Democratic Union/meta/color}} |party_name      = Croatian Democratic Union |native_name     = Hrvatska demokratska zajednica |party_logo      = [[File:HDZ logo.svg|220px]] |president       = [[Tomislav Karamarko]] |secretary       = [[Milijan Brkić]]  |founder         = [[Franjo Tuđman]] |foundation      = {{Start date|1989|06|17|df=y}} |headquarters    = [[Zagreb]], [[Croatia]] |membership_year = 2013 |membership      = 210,000<ref name="clanstvo">[http://www.vecernji.hr/hrvatska/hns-vesne-pusic-ima-vise-clanova-od-milanoviceva-sdp-a-625615]</ref> |youth_wing      = [[Youth of the Croatian Democratic Union]] |ideology        = [[Croatian nationalism]]<br>[[National conservatism]]<br>[[Conservatism]]<ref name="Nordsieck">[http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/croatia.html Parties and Elections in Europe: The database about parliamentary elections and political parties in Europe, by Wolfram Nordsieck]</ref><br>[[Christian democracy]]<ref name="Nordsieck"/><br>[[Pro-Europeanism]] |position        =  [[Centre-right]]<ref name="JansenHecke">{{Citation |first1=Thomas |last1=Jansen |first2=Steven |last2=Van Hecke |title=At Europe's Service: The Origins and Evolution of the European People's Party |publisher=Springer |year=2011 |page=79 |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kXEA8XGdEb8C&pg=PA79&dq=croatian+democratic+union+pro+european&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LPRXT_2cB6XK0QXx18DEDQ&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=croatian%20democratic%20union%20pro%20european&f=false |accessdate=2012-07-26}}</ref> to [[Right-wing]]<ref name="Dio98">{{Citation |first1=Dio |last1=Dio |last2=98 |title=Croatia PM Accuses Right-Wingers of Ethnic Hate |publisher=Balkan Transitional Justice |year=2014 |url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/croatian-pm-right-parties-spread-hate |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref><ref name="Dio">{{Citation |first1=Dio |last2=98 |title=Croatian Democratic Union |publisher=Encyclopedia Britannica |year=2014 |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/143619/Croatian-Democratic-Union |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref><ref>http://www.oslobodjenje.ba/daily-news/hdz-croatia-communist-totalitarianism-should-be-clearly-condemned</ref> |religion        = [[Roman Catholicism]] |international   = [[Centrist Democrat International]],<br> [[International Democrat Union]] |european        = [[European People's Party]] |europarl        = [[European People's Party (European Parliament group)|European People's Party]] |seats1_title    = [[Sabor]] |seats1          = {{Composition bar|41|151|hex={{Croatian Democratic Union/meta/color}}}}  |seats2_title    = [[European Parliament]] |seats2          = {{Composition bar|4|11|hex={{Croatian Democratic Union/meta/color}}}} |colours         = [[Blue]] |website         = {{URL|www.hdz.hr}} |country         = Croatia }}  The '''Croatian Democratic Union''' ({{lang-hr|Hrvatska demokratska zajednica}} {{IPA-sh|xř̩ʋaːtskaː demǒkratskaː zâjednit͡sa|}}, commonly known under acronym '''HDZ''') is a [[conservative]] political party and the main [[center-right]] political party in [[Croatia]]. It is one of the [[List of political parties in Croatia|two major contemporary political parties in Croatia]], along with the [[centre-left]] [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP). It is currently the second-largest party in the Croatian Parliament with 41 seats. HDZ ruled Croatia from 1990 to 2000 and, in coalition with junior partners, from 2003 to 2011. The party is a member of the [[European People's Party]] (EPP).  ==History==  ===Origins=== The HDZ was founded in 17 June 1989 by Croatian dissidents led by [[Franjo Tuđman]]. When the party was founded, the multi-party system in Croatia was at an embryonic stage. The HDZ was founded in an almost conspiratorial manner, and its first offices were in a Zagreb shack. Because of that the party founders proudly call themselves ''barakaši'' - from "baraka", which is the Croatian word for "shack".  President Tuđman and other HDZ officials traveled abroad and gathered large financial contributions from Croatian expatriates.  On the eve of the [[Croatian parliamentary election, 1990|1990 elections]], the ruling [[Croatian Communist Party]] saw such tendencies within the HDZ as an opportunity to remain in power. At the beginning of democracy the communists called HDZ "the party of dangerous intentions". At the elections this proved to be miscalculation, because 41.9% of Croatian voters saw the chance to be free from communism and [[Yugoslavia]], but also as the proper answer to Serb nationalism, embodied in part by [[Slobodan Milošević]].{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} The HDZ won a majority in the Croatian Parliament, and Croatia became one of the few countries of Eastern Europe where Communist single party rule was replaced by anti-Communist single party rule. May 30, 1990 - the day the HDZ formally took power - was later celebrated as Statehood Day, a public holiday in Croatia.  ===Tuđman presidency=== [[File:FranjoTudman.JPG|thumb|right|[[Franjo Tuđman]], former [[Croatian President]] and HDZ Founder]]  The [[Croatian presidential election, 1992|presidential elections]] followed in 1992 and Tuđman, who would remain as undisputed party leader until his death in 1999, was elected president.  The party ruled Croatia throughout the 1990s and under its leadership, Croatia became independent (1991), was internationally recognised (1992), and consolidated all of its pre-war territory (by 1998). During that period, the HDZ won both the 1992 and 1995 parliamentary elections.  As it strongly advocated Croatian independence, the HDZ was quite unpopular with the [[Serb]] minority, and others who preferred to see [[Croatia]] remain inside the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]]. This was one of the factors contributing to the creation of the [[Republic of Serbian Krajina]] and the subsequent armed conflict in neighbouring [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]]. The role of the HDZ in those events is matter of controversy, even in Croatia, where some tend to view HDZ policy in the early stages of the conflict as extremist and a contributing factor in the escalation of violence, while others (such as [[Marko Veselica]]'s [[Croatian Democratic Party]]) see the HDZ as having appeased [[Serbia]] and the [[Yugoslav People's Army]], and therefore, being responsible for Croatia being unprepared for defence.<ref>{{cite book|last=Špegelj|first=Martin|title=Sjećanja vojnika|year=2001|publisher=Znanje|location=Zagreb|isbn=953-195-190-X|edition=1. izd.}}</ref> However, the policies of Tuđman and the HDZ shifted according to the circumstances.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}  === Transition to capitalism ===  The HDZ also began to lead Croatia toward [[post-Communism|political and economic transition]] from communism to capitalism. Notably, HDZ governments implemented [[privatization]] in the country, in a manner that critics consider sub-optimal, and at times possibly illegal, due to the selective nature of the [[nationalization]]s (see [[Croatian privatization controversy]]). According to the HDZ, this process proved a useful distraction from dealing with the baggage of post World War II communist nationalizations. In fact it was the HDZ in 1992 which enacted into law the right of [[corporation]]s (the vast majority of which were under state ownership) the right to finally formally register themselves as the owners of nationalized property, thus completing their own version of a process of quasi-nationalization started by the communist regime after WWII, in different targeted areas for their own gain.  As a result of these, and other, schemes, that had been planned before the break-up of Yugoslavia, many "[[tycoon]]s" emerged in a pattern of state-sponsored loans brokered with HDZ influence, with the purpose of dissolving state ownership. This model was widely abused, not only by the HDZ, but also by other political parties.  Not all of the nationalized property was dealt with in this way. The property of those who could lobby the HDZ, or who had substantial influence in Croatian politics, was returned without much delay, while others had to wait for justice. Property returned included possessions nationalized from the [[Catholic Church in Croatia|Catholic Church]] or from widely known individuals such as Gavrilović, the owner of a major meat-producing factory in [[Petrinja]], south of Zagreb. Restitution for land seized during the break-up of Yugoslavia is still of great public concern.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}  ===HDZ after Tuđman's death=== {{Politics of Croatia}} All this, together with Tuđman's death in December 1999, had an impact on the [[Croatian parliamentary election, 2000|2000 parliamentary elections]]. Although the HDZ remained the largest single party, it was defeated by a left-centre coalition of six opposition parties and many saw the large turnout as a referendum against the HDZ, just as the 1990 elections had been seen as a referendum on Communism and Yugoslavia. This impression was underlined at the subsequent [[Croatian presidential election, 2000|presidential election]], when the HDZ candidate [[Mate Granić]], heavily favoured to win, finished third and therefore failed to enter the second round of voting, won by [[Stjepan Mesić|Stipe Mesić]].  In the period from 2000 and 2003, several businessmen who became tycoons under the initial HDZ rule were tried and convicted for alleged abuses, though in general the privatization process implemented by the HDZ remained unaltered.  This period proved to be a low point for the HDZ and many thought that party could not recover. Those included Mate Granić, who, together with [[Vesna Škare-Ožbolt]], left to form the centre-right [[Democratic Centre (Croatia)|Democratic Centre]] (DC).  The HDZ began to recover when the [[ICTY|International Criminal Tribunal]] began to prosecute [[Croatian Army]] commanders, thus provoking a major backlash among the Croatian public. Popular discontent manifested itself in mass rallies as the public came to terms with the changes in the party and its policies. Although the HDZ, and its new leader [[Ivo Sanader]], took part in those events and supported the protests, they gradually began to distance themselves from the more extreme rhetoric, becoming perceived as moderates. This tendency continued when the [[Croatian Social Liberal Party]] shifted rightwards, making Sanader's HDZ appear centrist in comparison. This process was completed in 2002 when [[Ivić Pašalić]], leader of the HDZ hardliners and perceived to be associated with the worst excesses of Tuđman's era, challenged Sanader for the party leadership, accusing him of betraying Tuđman's nationalist legacy. At first it looked that Sanader would lose, but with the help of [[Branimir Glavaš]] and the tacit support of liberal sections of Croatian public opinion, he won at the party convention. Pašalić then left the HDZ to form the [[Croatian Bloc (political party)|Croatian Bloc]] party.  This allowed Sanader to present the HDZ as a "reforming" party, one that would completely face what they had created, purged of some of the more controversial aspects of the Tuđman legacy, and to convince the public that returning the HDZ to power would not jeopardise democratic standards in Croatia. As such, the HDZ started to be perceived as a credible democratic alternative to the government of [[Ivica Račan]], then plagued by the same indecision, inefficiency, corruption and factional struggles, though it was the tip of the iceberg with much more to come.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}  ===First Sanader government 2003–2008=== [[File:Sanader cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Ivo Sanader]], president of the Croatian Democratic Union from 2000 - 2009]] At the [[Croatian parliamentary elections, 2003|legislative elections of November 2003]], the party won 33.9% of the popular vote and 66 out of 151 seats. Although it failed to win a clear majority in the [[Croatian Parliament]], even with the help of the allied DC and HSLS, it formed a government with the nominally left-wing [[Independent Democratic Serb Party]] and the [[Croatian Party of Pensioners]].  With such a broad and diverse mandate, the Sanader-led government vigorously pursued policies that amounted to the implementation of the basic criteria for joining the [[European Union]], such as the return of refugees to their homes, rebuilding houses damaged in the war, improving minority rights by including minority representatives in the government, cooperating with the ICTY, and continuing to consolidate the Croatian economy. Despite this, the EU's Council of Ministers postponed Croatia's membership negotiations with the union on the grounds of its non-cooperation with the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] over the case of indicted general [[Ante Gotovina]].  This setback brought an increase in [[Eurosceptic]] views among the Croatian public, which also affected support for the HDZ. Since accession to the EU was a key part of Sanader's reformist course, opposition to his leadership within and outside HDZ was on the rise. This opposition manifested itself at the 2005 local elections and the defection of Glavaš, who not only successfully challenged Sanader's authority but also managed to nominally deprive Sanader of his parliamentary majority.  ===Second Sanader government 2008-2009===  Despite this defeat, the first Sanader led government was able to survive until the end of the legislature. The subsequent [[Croatian parliamentary election, 2007|parliamentary election]] in late November 2007 saw the HDZ hard-pressed both by the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|SDP]]-led leftist coalition and by the extreme right wing [[Croatian Party of Rights]] and [[Croatian Democratic Assembly of Slavonia and Baranja]].  During the electoral campaign a vigorous and sometimes ruthless reaction from the party and Sanader himself, together with some capital errors from SDP, convinced part of the far right electorate to support the HDZ in order to prevent what they perceived as the heirs of the former [[Communism|communist]] party to return to power.<ref>[http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/vote-for-hsp-is-vote-for-sdp---sanader_82105 Vote for HSP Is Vote for SDP – Sanader - Current Events - Croatia - Dalje.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.studiacroatica.org/bol2007/20070912_diaspora.htm PM: Nobody Will Take Away Votes from Diaspora<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The party won a majority of both seats and votes in the election, and the first session of the newly elected parliament was called for 11 January 2008. However, the SDP repeatedly refused to acknowledge defeat, claiming that they had the most votes if the [[Diaspora]] ballot was not taken into account. The HDZ gained the support of the "yellow green coalition" (HSS-HSLS) and of the HSU and [[national minorities]] representatives, and so a second government, still led by [[Ivo Sanader]], was formed.  Although that government had a larger majority than the former one, its existence remained troubled, because of the worsening of the previously good economic situation and a [[weariness]] of Croatian public opinion about what was felt to be an overly long HDZ rule.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} Another major drawback was the [[Slovenia]]n blocking of several chapters of Croatia's EU accession terms, until border disputes between the two countries had been settled.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} Although this ultimately lead to an indefinite suspension of the Croatian [[European Union|EU]] accession negotiations, it had no impact on the government's popularity. In this case, as would be expected, considering Croatian staunch [[patriotism]] and national [[self-consciousness]], all parties and nearly every Croatian [[citizen]] were absolutely adamant in refusing at any cost any concessions over matters of [[national interest]].{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}  In [[Croatian local elections, 2009|the general local elections]] held in May 2009, the HDZ, against all expectations, managed to grow again, coming ahead of the SDP.<ref>[http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2009/05/21/feature-03 Croatia's local elections head to second round (SETimes.com)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> However, HDZ support did weaken in the larger cities.  On 1 July 2009, Ivo Sanader abruptly announced his resignation from politics and appointed [[Jadranka Kosor]] as his successor. She was confirmed as the new leader of the party on 4 July, and was appointed by president Stipe Mesic as the prime minister-designate. Two days later the [[Sabor]] confirmed Kosor as the new [[Prime Minister of Croatia|prime minister]], the first woman to hold the position.  In the same resignation speech, Sanader also appointed [[Andrija Hebrang (son)|Andrija Hebrang]], who had formerly held the posts of [[Ministry of Defence (Croatia)|defence minister]] and [[Ministry of Health and Social Welfare (Croatia)|health minister]], as HDZ candidate for the incoming [[Croatian presidential election, 2009-2010|presidential election]], so decreasing any speculation about his own ambitions for that position.  ===Government of Jadranka Kosor=== [[File:Flickr - europeanpeoplesparty - EPP Summit March 2010 (43).jpg|thumb|[[Jadranka Kosor]], president of the Croatian Democratic Union from 2009 until 2012]] The HDZ was faced with bad poll ratings and a large clean-up task that was still underway when Sanader left. The officials used the 2009 convention to elect Jadranka Kosor the party president by acclamation, and proceeded to make various unpopular measures to tackle the economic crisis. [[Andrija Hebrang (son)|Andrija Hebrang]] accepted his designation as the presidential candidate only at the end of July, after he underwent a thorough [[medical examination]], to exclude any remaining trace of a previous [[carcinoma]].  The Kosor government remained mostly unchanged from the previous Sanader government, but the HDZ suffered some internal turmoil as ministers [[Berislav Rončević]] and [[Damir Polančec]] left their posts after allegations of corruption.   In the next presidential elections, Croatia was looking for a replacement for [[Stipe Mesić]] who had held the position for ten years. But Hebrang finished third, failing to reach the second stage in which SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipović]] overwhelmingly defeated former SDP member [[Milan Bandić]].  However, many Croatian people were dissatisfied with the government, and protested on the streets against the HDZ government, demanding that new elections be held as soon as possible. The police placed a guard on [[St. Mark's Square, Zagreb|St. Mark's Square]], to prevent civilians from entering.<ref>[http://danas.net.hr/hrvatska/page/2011/02/27/0033006.html Hrvatska ključa - spremaju se novi prosvjedi - Danas.hr<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  From 26 October 2011 [[USKOK]] expanded its investigation about "Slush Funds" on Croatian Democratic Union as legal entity.<ref name=CaparToma>Capar, Luka; Toma, Ivanka. [http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/j-kosor-necu-dati-ostavku-necemo-dopustiti-da-se-hdz-urusi-clanak-340569 J. Kosor: Neću dati ostavku i nećemo dopustiti da se HDZ uruši]. [[Večernji list]]. 2011-10-27. Retrieved 2011-10-27 {{hr icon}}</ref> Previously, investigation included only [[Ivo Sanader]], treasurers [[Milan Barišić]] and [[Branka Pavošević]], general secretaries [[Branko Vukelić]] and [[Ivan Jarnjak]] and spokesman [[Ratko Maček]].<ref name=CaparToma/> [[Jadranka Kosor]], president of the party, stated that this is one of the most critical moments of Croatian Democratic Union.<ref name=CaparToma/> HDZ became the first political party in Croatia to be accused of corruption.<ref name=EA>{{cite web |url=http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/kosor-ne-postoje-tajni-dogovori-o-nagodbi-s-dorh-om.html |title=Kosor: Ne postoje tajni dogovori o nagodbi s DORH-om |author=E., A. |date=16 April 2012 |work= |publisher=[[Dnevnik Nove TV]] |language=Croatian |accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref>  ===In the opposition=== [[File:Tomislav Karamarko 2009.JPG|thumb|Tomislav Karamarko, president of the HDZ from 2012]] After the [[Croatian parliamentary election, 2011|parliamentary election]], held in December 2011, HDZ become the opposition after 8 years spent in government. Since its foundation, HDZ won its smallest number of votes, 563,215.  On 20 May 2012, HDZ held a presidential election in which, a day later, [[Tomislav Karamarko]] become the winner<ref name=Vecernji>{{cite news |title='Prošlo je vrijeme komocije i eksperimentiranja s Hrvatskom' |author1=Grubišić, petar |author2=Ivanković, Davor |author3=Balija, Petra |author4=Kožul, Dijana |author5=Capar Luka |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/proslo-je-vrijeme-komocije-eksperimentiranja-hrvatskom-clanak-411574 |newspaper=[[Večernji list]] |date=21 May 2012 |language=Croatian |accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref> and thus replaced Kosor as leader of the [[Opposition (Croatia)|oppostion]]. Karamarko announced that he would reestablish connections between Croatia and the [[Croatian diaspora]].<ref name=Vecernji/>  Karamarko earlier announced that, after a process of the [[Tudjmanism|detudjmanization]] of the HDZ, he would return to the policies of Franjo Tuđman. He also stated that he would not base his politics on the teachings of [[Ante Pavelić]] or [[Josip Broz Tito]], as both of them represented totalitarian systems.<ref name=Opacak-Klobucar>{{cite news |title=Karamarko: Ni za Pavelića ni za Tita, moramo se vratiti Tuđmanu |author=Opačak-Klobučar, Tamara |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/karamarko-ni-pavelica-ni-tita-moramo-se-vratiti-tudmanu-clanak-407309 |newspaper=[[Večernji list]] |date=8 May 2012 |language=Croatian |accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref> On the 1st July 2013, HDZ received full member status of the [[European People's Party]] (EPP).<ref>{{cite news |title=Croatia’s EU accession brings stability to the region; HDZ becomes full member party of the EPP |url=http://news.epp.eu/zzdPwC|date=1 July 2013}}</ref> On the 11th of March 2014, HDZ and [[Ivo Sanader]] were found guilty of corruption.<ref>{{cite web  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26533990  | title = Former Croatia PM Ivo Sanader convicted of corruption | date = 11 March 2014}}</ref>  ==Ideology== In terms of ideology, HDZ leaders at first described their party as [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]], and Tuđman himself stated that he was inspired by [[Thatcherism]]. Later, the party described itself as [[centre-right]] and [[Christian Democrat]]. However, the only official ideology was [[nationalism]]. In practice, this policy saw the powerful defence minister [[Gojko Šušak]], head of the HDZ hardline faction, win Tuđman's favour. [[Stjepan Mesić]] and [[Josip Manolić]], Tuđman's associates opposed to such tendencies, left the party in 1994 and formed the [[Croatian Independent Democrats]]. These tendencies were toned down after the end of the war and the HDZ, concerned with more mundane aspects of politics, became a mainly [[social conservative]] party.  The end of war and reintegration of Croatian territory also switched Croatian people's attention from independence and foreign relations to the more mundane issues of the economy and living standards. In the late 1990s this coincided with Tuđman's illness, which sparked bitter succession struggles between various factions within the HDZ. These factions fought using friendly media and by leaking compromising information about their opponents' roles in the shadier aspects of privatisation. This, as well as Tuđman's mishandling of the [[Zagreb Crisis]], did much to undermine HDZ credibility.  ==Election history==  ===Legislative=== The following is a summary of the party's results in legislative elections for the [[Croatian Parliament]]. The "Total votes" and "Percentage" columns include sums of votes won by pre-election coalitions HDZ had been part of and the "Total seats" column includes sums of seats won by HDZ in election constituencies plus representatives of ethnic minorities affiliated with HDZ.  {| class="wikitable" style="text-align: left;" |- !width="120" rowspan="2"|Election !width="160" rowspan="2"|In coalition with !width="100"|Votes won !width="100"|Percentage!!width="100"|Seats won !width="100"|Change |- ! colspan="2" | {{small|(Coalition totals)}} !! colspan="2" | {{small|(HDZ only)}} |- |[[Croatian parliamentary election, 1990|1990 {{small|(April–May)}}]] |''None'' |align="right"|1,201,122 |align="right"|41.90% |align="center"| 205 / 351 |{{n/a}} |- |[[Croatian parliamentary election, 1992|1992 {{small|(August)}}]] |''None'' |align="right"|1,176,437 |align="right"|44.68% |align="center"|85 / 138 |align="center"|–120 |- |[[Croatian parliamentary election, 1995|1995 {{small|(October)}}]] |''None'' |align="right"|1,093,403 |align="right"|45.23% |align="center"|75 / 127 |align="center"|–10 |- |[[Croatian parliamentary election, 2000|2000 {{small|(January)}}]] |''None'' |align="right"|790,728 |align="right"|26.88% |align="center"|46 / 151 |align="center"|–29 |- |[[Croatian parliamentary election, 2003|2003 {{small|(November)}}]] |''None'' |align="right"|840,692 |align="right"|33.90% |align="center"|66 / 151 |align="center"|+20 |- |[[Croatian parliamentary election, 2007|2007 {{small|(November)}}]] |''None'' |align="right"|907,743 |align="right"|36.60% |align="center"|66 / 153 |align="center"|— |- |[[Croatian parliamentary election, 2011|2011 {{small|(December)}}]] |[[Croatian Civic Party|HGS]]–[[Democratic Centre (Croatia)|DC]] | style="text-align:right;"|563,215 | style="text-align:right;"|23.50% |align="center"|44 / 151 |align="center"|–22 |}  ===Presidential=== *[[Croatian presidential election, 1992|1992]] – [[Franjo Tuđman]] (Won, with 56.7% of votes in first round) *[[Croatian presidential election, 1997|1997]] – [[Franjo Tuđman]] (Won, with 61.4% of votes in first round) *[[Croatian presidential election, 2000|2000]] – [[Mate Granić]] (Finished third with 22.5% of votes in first round) *[[Croatian presidential election, 2005|2005]] – [[Jadranka Kosor]] (Finished second with 20.3% of votes in first round and was runner-up in second round with 34.1% of votes) *[[Croatian presidential election, 2009–10|2009–10]] – [[Andrija Hebrang (son)|Andrija Hebrang]] (Finished third with 12.04% of votes in first round) *[[Croatian presidential election, 2014–15|2014–15]] – [[Kolinda Grabar-Kitarović]] (Finished second with 37.2% of votes in first round and won in second round with 50.7% of votes)  ===European parliament=== {| class="wikitable" style="text-align: left;" |- ! style="width:120px;"|Election!! style="width:140px;"|In coalition with!! style="width:100px;"|Votes won<br /><small>(Coalition totals)</small>!! style="width:100px;"|Percentage!! style="width:100px;"|Total seats won<br /> <small>(HDZ only</small>!! style="width:100px;"|Change |- |[[European Parliament election, 2013 (Croatia)|April 2013]]<ref>[[European Parliament election, 2013 (Croatia)#Results]]</ref> |[[Croatian Party of Rights dr. Ante Starčević]], [[Bloc of United Pensioners]] |align="right"|243,654 |align="right"|32,86% | style="text-align:center;"|{{Composition bar|5|12|hex={{Croatian Democratic Union/meta/color}}}} | style="text-align:center;"|{{steady}} |- |[[European Parliament election, 2014 (Croatia)|May 2014]]<ref>http://www.novilist.hr/Vijesti/Hrvatska/Prebrojani-svi-glasovi-DIP-sluzbeno-objavio-imena-11-europarlamentaraca</ref> |[[Croatian Party of Rights dr. Ante Starčević]], [[Bloc of United Pensioners]], [[Croatian Peasant Party]], [[Croatian Demochristian Party]], [[Zagorska  democratic party]] |align="right"|381.844 |align="right"|41,42% | style="text-align:center;"|{{Composition bar|4|11|hex={{Croatian Democratic Union/meta/color}}}} | style="text-align:center;"|{{decrease}}1 |}  ==See also== * [[Elections in the Croatian Democratic Union]] * [[Croatian Democratic Union of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]  ==References== {{reflist}} {{Croatian political parties}} {{European People's Party}} {{International Democrat Union}}  [[Category:Croatian nationalism]] [[Category:Christian democratic parties]] [[Category:Conservative parties in Croatia]] [[Category:Catholic political parties]] [[Category:Nationalist parties in Croatia]] [[Category:International Democrat Union member parties]] [[Category:Political parties established in 1989]] [[Category:Member parties of the European People's Party]]</text></page>",
"<page><title>Wikipedia:Village pump (proposals)/Archive 84</title><text>{{Wikipedia:Village pump/Archive header}}  == Waiting edit requests to the global block notice ==  There are two waiting edit requests at [[MediaWiki talk:Globalblocking-blocked]].[[User:Jasper Deng|Jasper Deng]] [[User talk:Jasper Deng|(talk)]] 05:18, 16 January 2012 (UTC) == Call talk pages "Talk" ==  <div class="boilerplate metadata vfd xfd-closed" style="background-color: #F3F9FF; margin: 2em 0 0 0; padding: 0 10px 0 10px; border: 1px solid #AAAAAA;"> :''The following discussion is an archived record of a [[WP:RFC|request for comment]]. <span style="color:red">'''Please do not modify it.'''</span>  No further edits should be made to this discussion.  {{#if:|''A summary of the conclusions reached follows.'' ::{{{1}}}|A summary of the debate may be found at the bottom of the discussion.''}} <!-- Template:rfc top   Note:  If you are seeing this page as a result of an attempt to register a new request for comment, you must manually edit the nomination links in order to create a new discussion page using the name format of [[Wikipedia:Requests for comment/''subject'' (Second)]].  When you create the new discussion page, please provide a link to this old discussion.  -->  ''Consensus is in favor of changing the discussion link to '''Talk'''. Those in favor cite many reasons why this change will stimulate new editor participation, while most who oppose only state personal preference. They 'ayes' have it.'' <span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'"> — [[User:Edokter|<span style="color:#008"><i>E</i>dokter</span>]] ([[User talk:Edokter|<span style="color:#080">talk</span>]]) — </span> 16:30, 9 January 2012 (UTC) :The discussion consensus was enacted in [http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MediaWiki:Talk&diff=470458069 this edit] to [[MediaWiki:Talk]]. [[User:Cunard|Cunard]] ([[User talk:Cunard|talk]]) 08:55, 16 January 2012 (UTC)  ----  RfC tag added on 09:01, 4 December 2011 (UTC).  Hi. A lot of Wikipedia instructions tell people to post "on the talk page". However, it isn't obvious where this means, since the page is not labelled "talk page" but is labelled "discussion". This is very confusing, especially for someone unfamiliar with all the Wikipedia rules. Wny not change the text on the tab from "Discussion" to "Talk page" to match all the instructions? (By instructions I am referring to everything you get when you click Help, as well as so many of the templates used to tell posters why their edit was not accepted and how to fix it. ([[Special:Contributions/184.147.120.119|184.147.120.119]] ([[User talk:184.147.120.119|talk]]) 23:07, 2 December 2011 (UTC))   <small>''Just a note: the page which will need to be changed is [[MediaWiki:Talk]]. [[User talk:Sonia|<font color="#CC0099">sonia</font>]]♫ 09:48, 4 December 2011 (UTC)</small><br>  <small>'' At 17:14, 8 December 2011 (UTC) I changed the title of the post from 'Call talk pages "Talk Page"' to 'Call talk pages "Talk"', because there is a massive consensus among people supporting this change for using 'Talk' in specific and some opposition to 'Talk Page' in specific. [[User:Sven Manguard|<font color="207004"><big>'''S</big>ven <big>M</big>anguard'''</font>]] [[User talk:Sven Manguard|<small><font color="F0A804">'''Wha?'''</font></small>]] 17:14, 8 December 2011 (UTC)</small>  *'''Support''' this one per 2011 "State of the Wiki" address. ''[[User:Rich Farmbrough|Rich]]&nbsp;[[User talk:Rich Farmbrough|Farmbrough]]'', <small>23:39, 2 December 2011 (UTC).</small><br /> *'''Support continuity''' I don't much mind which is prefered or even if another name like "chatter" or "gobledigook" (well maybe not) is chosen, but I do think we would be better off with one name for all "talk pages" across the whole site.&nbsp;[[User:Fred_Gandt|'''<span style="font-family:arial;font-size:130%;color:#044;">f<i style="color:#0dd;font-size:60%;">red</i>g<i style="color:#0dd;font-size:60%;">andt</i></span>''']] 00:42, 3 De