things try to avoid) and is considered a leak of private information contrary to Wikimedia's privacy policy. [[User:Anomie|Anomie]][[User talk:Anomie|⚔]] 03:16, 20 January 2012 (UTC) ::I suppose I understand what you're saying, though I fail to see how this minor reliance on a third-party service would cause any issues. Also, what private information? Why shouldn't we be able to see an accurate count of Wikipedia's visitors? [[User:Kinaro|'''<font face="Bradley Hand ITC" size="3px" color="green">Kinaro</font>''']]<sup>[[User talk:Kinaro|(say hello)''']]</sup> <sup>[[Special:Contributions/Kinaro|(what's been done)]]</sup> 04:39, 20 January 2012 (UTC) :::The issue is enabling a third party to track every individual's use of Wikipedia. This would break the bond of trust with the readers. If the quantcast server isn't run by Wikimedia, there's no guarantee that the information will only be used in line with Wikimedia's goals. The Quantcast page you link to says "Estimate only" (and their measurements can't include users without Javascript), yet [http://stats.grok.se/ the stats server] gives raw hit numbers, so on the face of it your explanation is the wrong way round. [[User:MartinPoulter|MartinPoulter]] ([[User talk:MartinPoulter|talk]]) 13:38, 20 January 2012 (UTC) :"more reliable and accurate traffic data, as well as page view data not available under current estimated data methods" data is available, but it is not published [[User:Bulwersator|Bulwersator]] ([[User talk:Bulwersator|talk]]) 14:07, 20 January 2012 (UTC) ::I think knowing how often one article is linked from or to another would be very useful. I can see the amount of data involved would be quite large but I believe it is manageable. I don't believe Javascript would be needed for any of this. [[User:Dmcq|Dmcq]] ([[User talk:Dmcq|talk]]) 14:22, 20 January 2012 (UTC) :::Eeeee... What? This data is available, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:WhatLinksHere/Wikipedia:Village_pump_%28proposals%29 [[Use